{
    "node_id": "time-matrix-18",
    "title": "Reporting the Past: Past Passive",
    "description": "Using the past passive voice to report finished events.",
    "display_order": 18,
    "prerequisites": ["time-matrix-17"],
    "lesson_content_markdown": "# Reporting the Past: Past Passive\n\nThe **Past Passive** is used when we want to talk about something that happened in the past, but the object is more important than the person who did the action.\n\n### 1. How to Make It\nUse the **Past Be Verb** (was / were) + the **Past Participle** (V3).\n\n- **Formula**: was/were + V3\n- **Example**: The email **was sent** yesterday at 5:00.\n- **Example**: The surveys **were conducted** in 2022.\n\n### 2. Singular vs. Plural\n- **Singular**: The book **was written** in 1990.\n- **Plural**: The books **were written** in 1990.\n\n### 3. When to use it?\n- **Reporting**: \"The results **were published** in the university journal.\"\n- **History**: \"The new building **was opened** last semester.\"\n- **Science**: \"The sample **was cooled** to 0 degrees.\"\n\n---",
